Pakistan and India gained independence from British colonial rule in 1947, and since then, the two countries have been engaged in a number of conflicts, including three major wars in 1947, 1965, and 1971.
The 1947 Partition of India resulted in the formation of Pakistan as a Muslim-majority nation and India as a secular, democratic state with a Hindu majority.

The dispute over the Kashmir region has been a major source of tension between Pakistan and India. Both countries claim the region in its entirety, but control only parts of it. The dispute has resulted in several military conflicts and border skirmishes over the years.

The Mumbai terrorist attacks in 2008, carried out by a Pakistan-based militant group, severely strained the already tense relationship between the two countries. India blamed Pakistan for the attacks and demanded that the perpetrators be brought to justice.

Despite the tensions, Pakistan and India have made several attempts to improve relations over the years. In 1999, the Lahore Declaration was signed between the two countries, which aimed to improve bilateral relations and promote peace and stability in the region.

In 2018, Pakistani Prime Minister Imran Khan invited Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi to attend his inauguration ceremony, which was seen as a positive step towards improving relations. However, the relationship soured again in the aftermath of a terrorist attack in Pulwama, India, in 2019.

The two countries have engaged in several confidence-building measures over the years, such as bilateral talks, cultural exchanges, and trade agreements. However, progress towards a lasting peace has been slow and sporadic.

The nuclear capabilities of both Pakistan and India have added an extra layer of complexity to the relationship between the two countries. The two nations have engaged in a nuclear arms race, with both countries having developed nuclear weapons and missile delivery systems. The risk of a nuclear confrontation between the two nations is a major concern for the international community.

In 1971 India supported the independence movement in East Pakistan and provided refuge to millions of refugees who fled the violence and persecution in the region.

India responded by launching a military offensive on the eastern front, which quickly turned into a full-scale war.
The 1971 Pakistan-India war saw some of the largest tank battles in history, with both sides deploying their armoured units in large numbers.

In 1971 Pak India war the Pakistani navy attempted to blockade Indian ports, but was largely unsuccessful due to the superiority of the Indian navy.
